tary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]])\n* [[Chris Grayling]] ([[Leader of the House of Commons]] and the [[Lord President of the Council]])\n* [[Theresa Villiers]] ([[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]])\n* [[Priti Patel]] ([[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]])\n}}\n\nAt the time the referendum was called, the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] was [[Iain Duncan Smith]], who also supports leave. He subsequently resigned following the [[2016 United Kingdom budget]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35848687 |title=Iain Duncan Smith quits over planned disability benefit changes|website=BBC News|date=18 March 2016|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> Some suspected his resignation was due to his support for British withdrawal from the EU,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|title=Is Iain Duncan Smith's resignation about disability cuts \u2013 or Europe?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/mar/18/the-tory-war-over-brexit-that-made-iain-duncan-smith-fire-his-gun|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=The Guardian|date=18 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hutcheon|first1=Paul|title=IDS: is welfare reform or Europe behind his resignation?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/opinion/14371145.IDS__is_welfare_reform_or_Europe_behind_his_resignation_/|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=The Herald|date=20 March 2016}}</ref> but Duncan Smith has denied this, stating that such allegations were a \"deliberate attempt to discredit\" him.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCann|first1=Kate|title=Iain Duncan Smith resignation: EU claims are a 'deliberate attempt to discredit me' IDS claims after emotional Andrew Marr interview|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/12199301/iain-duncan-smith-resignation-reaction-live.html|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs well as these ministers, the former [[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]];<ref name=\"guardiansource\">{{cite web|title=Boris Johnson to campaign for Brexit in EU referendum|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/feb/21/boris-johnson-eu-referendum-campaign-for-brexit-david-cameron|website=The Guardian|publisher=Nicholas Watt|accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraphsource\">{{cite news|title=Fragile Tory truce over EU referendum shattered as David Cameron savages Boris Johnson|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/eureferendum/12167851/eu-referendum-david-cameron-faces-mps-after-boris-johnson-backs-brexit-live.html|website=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35626621|title=EU referendum: Time to vote for real change, says Boris Johnson|work=BBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> the Conservative candidate for the [[2016 London mayoral election|2016 mayoral election]], [[Zac Goldsmith]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-35625097|title=Tory candidate for London Mayor Zac Goldsmith will vote to leave EU|work=BBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> former leader [[Michael Howard]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jan/22/eu-referendum-michael-howard-hints-he-will-vote-for-brexit|title=EU referendum: Michael Howard hints he will vote for Brexit|author=Andrew Sparrow|work=The Guardian}}</ref> former [[Defence Secretary]] [[Liam Fox]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35144859|title=I'll vote to leave the EU, says former minister Liam Fox|date=20 December 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> and the leader of the [[Welsh Conservative Party]] [[Andrew R.T. Davies]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/welsh-tory-leader-andrew-rt-10930142#rlabs=1%20rt$category%20p$1|title=Welsh Tory leader Andrew RT Davies on why he wants to leave the EU|author=David Williamson|date=22 February 2016|work=walesonline|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> campaigned to leave. The party campaign to exit the EU is \"[[Conservatives for Britain]]\" which is headed by two former [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellors of the Exchequer]], Lord Lawson ([[Nigel Lawson]]) and Lord Lamont ([[Norman Lamont]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b53b3a1c-680a-11e5-97d0-1456a776a4f5.html |title=Lawson to head Tory eurosceptic drive|newspaper=Financial Times |accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nMany other Conservative MPs have announced that they will campaign for Britain to vote to Leave:<ref name=\"Rowena Mason\"/>{{Failed verification|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Stephen Barclay]] (North East Cambridgeshire)\n* [[John Baron (politician)|John Baron]] (Basildon and Billericay)\n* [[Victoria Borwick]] (Kensington)\n* [[Graham Brady]] (Altrincham and Sale West)\n* [[Julian Brazier]] (Canterbury)\n* [[Fiona Bruce (politician)|Fiona Bruce]] (Congleton)\n* [[Conor Burns]] (Bournemouth West)\n* [[Christopher Chope]] (Christchurch)\n* [[James Cleverly]] (Braintree)\n* [[Christopher Davies (Conservative politician)|Christopher Davies]] (Brecon and Radnorshire)\n* [[Nadine Dorries]] (Mid Bedfordshire)\n* [[George Eustice]] (Camborne and Redruth)\n* [[Michael Fabricant]] (Lichfield)\n* [[Liam Fox]] (North Somerset)\n* [[Richard Fuller (Bedford MP)|Richard Fuller]] (Bedford)\n* [[Cheryl Gillan]] (Chesham and Amersham)\n* [[Ian Liddell-Grainger]] (Bridgwater and West Somerset)\n* [[Chris Green (politician)|Chris Green]] (Bolton West)\n* [[Rebecca Harris]] (Castle Point)\n* [[Sir Gerald Howarth]] (Aldershot)\n* [[Ranil Jayawardena]] (North East Hampshire)\n* [[Edward Leigh]] (Gainsborough)\n* [[Karl McCartney]] (Lincoln)\n* [[Nigel Mills (politician)|Nigel Mills]] (Amber Valley)\n* [[Anne Marie Morris]] (Newton Abbot)\n* [[David Nuttall]] (Bury North)\n* [[Andrew Percy]] (Brigg and Goole)\n* [[Will Quince]] (Colchester)\n* [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]] (North East Somerset)\n* [[Bob Stewart (British Army officer)|Bob Stewart]] (Beckenham)\n* [[Desmond Swayne]] (New Forest West)\n* [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]] (Berwick-upon-Tweed)\n* [[Charles Walker (British politician)|Charles Walker]] (Broxbourne)\n* [[Martin Vickers]] (Cleethorpes)\n* [[David Jones (Clwyd West MP)|David Jones]] (Clwyd West)\n* [[Jason McCartney (politician)|Jason McCartney]] (Colne Valley)\n* [[Tom Pursglove]] (Corby)\n* [[Henry Smith (British politician)|Henry Smith]] (Crawley)\n* [[Gareth Johnson]] (Dartford)\n* [[Chris Heaton-Harris]] (Daventry)\n* [[Mike Wood (British Conservative politician)|Mike Wood]] (Dudley South)\n* [[Tim Loughton]] (East Worthing and Shoreham)\n* [[Greg Knight]] (East Yorkshire)\n* [[Mims Davies]] (Eastleigh)\n* [[David Burrowes]] (Enfield Southgate)\n* [[Eleanor Laing]] (Epping Forest)\n* [[Dominic Raab]] (Esher and Walton)\n* [[Suella Fernandes]] (Fareham)\n* [[Jack Lopresti]] (Filton and Bradley Stoke)\n* [[Rehman Chishti]] (Gillingham and Rainham)\n* [[Adam Holloway]] (Gravesham)\n* [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] (Haltemprice and Howden)\n* [[Bob Blackman (politician)|Bob Blackman]] (Harrow East)\n* [[Bernard Jenkin]] (Harwich and North Essex)\n* [[William Wragg]] (Hazel Grove)\n* [[Mike Penning]] (Hemel Hempstead)\n* [[Matthew Offord]] (Hendon)\n* [[Andrew Bingham]] (High Peak)\n* [[Peter Lilley]] (Hitchin and Harpenden)\n* [[Andrew Turner (politician)|Andrew Turner]] (Isle of Wight)\n* [[Philip Hollobone]] (Kettering)\n* [[Maria Caulfield]] (Lewes)\n* [[Michael Tomlinson]] (Mid Dorset and North Poole)\n* [[Iain Stewart (politician)|Iain Stewart]] (Milton Keynes South)\n* [[David T.C. Davies]] (Monmouth)\n* [[Andrea Jenkyns]] (Morley and Outwood)\n* [[Julian Lewis (politician)|Julian Lewis]] (New Forest East)\n* [[Scott Mann (politician)|Scott Mann]] (North Cornwall)\n* [[Bill Wiggin]] (North Herefordshire)\n* [[Owen Paterson]] (North Shropshire)\n* [[Justin Tomlinson]] (North Swindon)\n* [[C